      </p>

      <h2>Musical Style</h2>

      <p>
        Logic Moon's music merges <strong
          >ambient, drone and neoclassical</strong
        > influences. Typical are <strong
          >sound-painterly, cinematic soundscapes</strong
        > with electronic and acoustic elements. His pieces often begin with guitar
        or piano motifs, overlaid with flowing synthesizer drones, strings and field
        recordings. An example of this is the album <em
          >The Unavoidable Death of Loneliness</em
        >: It weaves "melodic piano and guitar lines" with dark string sounds
        and hammering rhythms, supported by old tube amplifiers and tape noise
        for warmth and humanity. Neoclassical components also appear – for
        example, the collaboration album <em>The Quiet Companion</em> (2023) is characterized
        by <strong
          >"gentle neoclassical pieces with piano, synthesizer pads and strings"</strong
        >. His <em>Lux</em> EP (2023), for example, is described as an "atmospheric
        sound tapestry" that combines contemporary ambient electronics with subtle
        neoclassical touches. Critics consistently praise the <strong
          >dense atmosphere</strong
        > and the mixture of organic and synthetic sounds – from bright guitar picking
        to texturally rich drone surfaces to quiet bird and nature recordings.
      </p>

      <h2>Special Works</h2>

      <p>
        Several works by Logic Moon found particular attention in the ambient
        community:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>"The Unavoidable Death of Loneliness" (2022)</strong> – a collaboration
          with Sven Laux. This album addresses the loneliness of the Corona pandemic.
          In reviews it is described as a seamless mix of post-classical and electronic
          ambient elements. Ambientblog writes that Laux and Lorsbach "merge post-classical
          arrangements and ambient soundscapes into adventurous, cinematic compositions."
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>"The Quiet Companion" (2023)</strong> – another joint long player
          with Sven Laux on Shimmering Moods Records. It consists of nine minimalist,
          neoclassically influenced instrumental pieces (with occasional vocals by
          Julia Gjertsen) and was praised by reviewers for its gentle harmony between
          piano, string and synthesizer sounds.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>"Ewiger Wald" (2024)</strong> and <strong
            >"Ewiger Wald Addendum" (2024)</strong
          > – two experimental mini albums with Swedish cellist Henrik Meierkord.
          In this project, Logic Moon and Meierkord explore a <em
            >"modern neoclassical ambient"</em
          > aesthetic by interweaving his emotional cello passages with Logic Moon's
          characteristic drones and synths. This double album (originally <em
            >Ewiger Wald</em
          > on Dronarivm, and the <em>Addendum</em> version with remixes) shows the
          fusion of electroacoustic elements with classical instrumentation.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Other noteworthy releases include <em>I See Planets</em> (2020, WhiteLabelRec),
        <em>Philia – Fountain</em> (2022) or <em>Sun</em> (2023), which resonated
        with fans and on various ambient playlists. Logic Moon also maintains an
        active YouTube channel with his music videos (mostly with sci-fi images)
        and curates ambient playlists, which additionally showcases his projects.
      </p>

      <h2>Collaborations</h2>

      <p>
        Logic Moon frequently works with other artists and labels. Significant
        collaborations include:
      </p>

      <ul>
